+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0138tVS9EHBm7aar5PckFDda","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"So in the boundary test, seed data has Jan: 10th, 25th (2 invoices), then it adds Jan 31st (total 3 for Jan). The test expects 3 but gets 4. That means the `2024-01-31` date is being counted in Jan AND something else is being counted wrong.\n\nThe issue is in `getMonthlyReport` at line 27: `new Date(inv.date + 'T00:00:00Z')`. Since the test sets `process.env.TZ = 'America/New_York'`, let me think about this...\n\nWait - the `'T00:00:00Z'` suffix makes it UTC, and `getMonth()` is local time. In the Eastern timezone, midnight UTC on Jan 31 would be Jan 30 at 7pm ET. So `getMonth()` would still return 0 (January). But for `2024-02-01T00:00:00Z`, `getMonth()` in ET would return 0 (January) because it's Jan 31 7pm ET.\n\nThat's the bug! `getMonth()` uses local time, but the date was parsed as UTC. So `2024-02-01T00:00:00Z` becomes Jan 31 in Eastern Time, and `getMonth()` returns 0 (January) instead of 1 (February).\n\nThe fix: use `getUTCMonth()` instead of `getMonth()`.\n\nLet me verify: the regression test on line 53 expects `march` to be defined for `2024-03-01`. With `getMonth()` in ET, `2024-03-01T00:00:00Z` becomes Feb 28 ET, so `getMonth()` returns 1 (February) not 2 (March). That matches the failure — `march` is undefined.\n\nNow I have all three bugs identified. Let me apply the fixes."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1135,"cache_read_input_tokens":28815,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1135},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3d4a42b1-0ecd-441b-9b6c-90c23458e03b","uuid":"ae44ace7-0998-46a4-a8ae-ef0a98441582"}
